{
  "answer": "**There is no passage in *Andreas* that names a specific number of days spent at sea.**\n\nThe poem describes Andrew's sea voyage to Mermedonia in vivid, metaphorical terms (e.g., boarding a divinely provided ship, a storm, divine intervention via angels carrying the sleepers ashore), but it provides no explicit duration like \"X days\" or \"X nights\" for time afloat.[^1][^2] Other numbered time periods appear, but they refer to Matthew's captivity (\"thirty days\"),[^3] Andrew's torments (\"three days\"),[^4] or his stay in the city (\"seven nights\"),[^5] not the sea journey itself.\n\n[^1]: *Andreas*, ch. 1, [¶ p-c4d450](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-c4d450) (instructions to find the ship; boarding and storm begin).\n[^2]: *Andreas*, ch. 1, [¶ p-c11ef8](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-c11ef8) (sleep; angels ferry them to land).\n[^3]: *Andreas*, ch. 1, [¶ p-58182e](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-58182e).\n[^4]: *Andreas*, ch. 1, [¶ p-dbf56f](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-dbf56f).\n[^5]: *Andreas*, ch. 1, [¶ p-ecb179](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-ecb179).",
